ce:section.ce:para:
Taking advantage of the excellent fluorescence properties of Cy7-CDs, the imaging performance for different types of live/dead bacteria cells (MRSA, G+ and E. coli (ATCC8739), G-) staining was first examined. It was found that the Cy7-CDs could rapidly interact with bacteria and almost no fluorescence, even without washing possible residual Cy7-CDs in PBS buffer. In contrast, the cell wall of live MRSA bacteria (G+) could be quickly reduced upon co-incubation with Cy7-CDs for 5 min under CLSM (Fig. 3
                        ). In particular, the fluorescence signal was significantly enhanced at 40 min, but still on the cell wall of live MRSA(G+), which could be as a fluorescent probe to long-term monitor the survival status of bacteria at different time (Fig. S5). However, live E. coli (ATCC8739, G-) displayed no clear fluorescence signals under the same conditions (Fig. 3). Meanwhile, the fluorescence signal of Cy7-CDs was barely detected by a microplate reader after being mixed with other G- bacteria (PA, E. Coli (ATCC27853), MRAB) (Fig. 4
                        A). Moreover, the zeta potential of the G- bacteria did not change significantly (Fig. 4B), thus indicating that the intact cell surface of the G- bacteria did not interact with the Cy7-CDs [53]. In addition, Cy7-CDs could quickly penetrate both dead G+ and G- bacteria through damaged cell membranes and emit strong fluorescence signals. The same phenomenon was observed with other bacteria (G+ bacteria: Streptococcus agalactiae, S. aureus, G- bacteria: P. aeruginosa, and A. baumannii) after being mixed with Cy7-CDs (Figs. S6 and 7).
